Home buying trends in Australia¶

This project will try and investigate the home buying trends in Australia. It will provide details on state-wide buying outcomes and its trend. The analysis will also share the trend on fist-time-home-buyers. Finally it will try and hypothise any corelation between property market volatility and COVID with NSW as a reference state.

The project will cover the following topics:

Summary of contents:

  1. Introduction
  2. Summary
  3. Data Inspection and Cleaning
  4. Analysis and Answers to Questions
  5. Conclusions and Discussion
  6. Future Analysis
  7. References

1. Introduction¶

Australia in the last 30 years has seen tremendous value assimilation on property. Our economy has been called as the “Goldie Locks” economy, where external and global indexes have had minimal impact. Exports of coal, iron ore and other natural resources have been fuelling the economy when world economy was under pressure in the years of 2000, 2008, 2018 (onwards), etc. This has clearly reflected in Australia’s purchasing parity. Strong economy, stable governments, robust exports, immigration support foreign policy has also provided push to the home purchasing in Australia.

Strong performances on home ownership and positive gearing over the last few decades has also been one of our strong indicators of economy. This paper reveals some of these trends in the last couple of decades. In 2019, the globe saw something which will would change our interactions with technology and would define how we spend our family times together. The global pandemic forced us to re-think approximately 200 years of way-of-working and skewed the work-life balance. Although the pandemic severely impacted industries such as Travel and Transportation, Manufacturing, Tourism, Retail, there were many other industries which took advantage of this pandemic. Retail giants quickly endorsed home-delivery. Multiple industry workers, students, and families; reluctantly first settled into the routine of work-from-home.

The ask for work-study-from-home meant a significant populace within Australia started thinking about property purchase. We would see in this paper, that there is sharp rise of first home buyers from 2020. Along with government policies of lower borrowing interest rates many first-home buyers took the plunge of buying property across Australia. We have seen these numbers consistently across all urban areas in Australia. This demand also had a cyclic impact on price increase, new property development, land-only sale and unit sales.

COVID could be only one reason for the price increase. We are showcasing this relationship with multiple data sources, i.e., from Australia Bureau of Statistics and focussing on NSW as a state to show the sharp rise of the various first-home buyers from NSW data site. Links to various datasets are shared below.

Questions to be answered

  1. Has there been an increase in Australia borrowing during the pandemic year?
  2. Has there been a change in the borrowing behaviour during pandemic time?
  3. Which state sells the maximum Units?
  4. Which state borrows the maximum?
  5. Has there been a significant rise in property market in NSW during recent years?
  6. Was there any corelation of a COVID spike in terms of the borrowing in NSW?

Data Files Used

560103 This file is imported in dataframe called new_borrow_df with columns including Unit Sales and Borrowing costs (in millions) for categories to include as land only, new dwellings, existing dwelling, alterations and repairs borrowing. We will use this file to categorise and represent answers to multiple questions wrt borrowing capability and state-wide representation. This excludes re-financing.

560104 This file provides the state-wide and national-wide borrowing for housing market at a summary level. This file is loaded on state_wide_df and includes columns for units and cost for all state wide data. We would represent this data to determine which states borrow the highest and have the highest unit sales.

NSW_COVID This file is downloaded from NSW health site (link provided in references) and represents confirmed COVID cases in NSW, for every post code. We would represent the highest confirmed COVID cases for each post code. This dataframe is loaded on NSW_COVID_df and is merged with state_wide_df, giving us a unique perspective of the impact of COVID on the buying behavious in NSW state.

Note: this file is over 122,000 row and takes a while to load on Ed. I have had experiences where the kernel needed restarting, so please be patient and if required, restart the kernel if prompted.

2. Summary¶

We have seen the trend over a 20 year period, although the multiple files and data points, clearly indicates that there has been a significant spike in first-time-home-buyers during the COVID months. The data also let us interpret the buying trends across various states in Australis during this time.

It is also a solid fact that there has been a high amount of borrowing for Renovation and Alteration, which has not been seen as a trend for last 20 years. From this trend, it could be seen that COVID has certainly driven Australians passion on home renovation.

4. Analysis and Answers to questions¶

Question 1: Has there been an increase in Australia borrowing during the pandemic year?

We see from the below graphs that for each category of borrowing including, new_dwelling, existing_dwelling, land_only and alterations_repairs cost, we could clearly see there has been a trend increase over last 20 years. From 2000 until 2018, the borrowing has been rather steady, although 2019 onwards, there is a clear spike in borrowings for every category of house.

Question 2: Has there been a change in the borrowing behaviour during pandemic time?

We have plotted a graph for the new_borrow_df with time. From the data point, we clearly see there has been a spike in land_only and alterations_repairs for home buyers. We could determine with a bit of certainity that during COVID time i.e. 2020 onwards, home buyers across the country have taken on projects including land_only and/or alterations and repairs to existing dwelling.

Note: is this a testimony of the Australian Spirit? data supports it, but the jury is out there.

Question 6: Was there any corelation of a COVID spike in terms of the borrowing in NSW?

We considered NSW as a representative state to map the NSW Covid data with NSW borrowing. On a conclusion, although we see there is an uptake of borrowing capacity during COVID, there isnt a signifcant corelation with the peak of COVID cases in NSW, which has been late 2021 and early 2022.

During the period of 2020, and 2021, there is definitely an increase in borrowing in NSW and it could be deducted that more people were fuelling the land price increase, which was seen in Australia. There could be various reasons for this, including lower interest rates from banks and a higher work-from-home adoption, resulting in higher number of Australians investing in properties.

Although visualising the graph, COVID peak in NSW has been late 2021 and early 2022. This period, has actually seen a slight dip in the borrowing, from the lofty 2020 and early 2021 period.

5. Conclusions and Discussion¶

There has been a significant increase in the housing market for Australia. We have seen this when answering Question 1. The increase has not only been in the availablity of units for sale, but also significantly higher sale of properties. The trend over the last 20 years has shown a strong Austrlian property market, and it has not shown any signs of slowing down even during the COVID period.

When responding to Question 2, 3 and 4, it is clearly demostrable that states such as NSW, Victoria, and Queensland (partially), are leading the housing market boom. NSW and Victoria have been the traditional stronghold and a good indicators of Australian property markets over the last few decades. Queensland market has shown stronger growth probably due to the Olympics Games announced for 2032.

States such as South Australia and Western Australia have shown steady increase in the cost, although cause of the density of these states, the number of units are clearly lagging NSW, Victoria and Queensland. Tasmania and Northern Territory has shown a stable and linear trend over the last 20 years.

We have considered NSW as a key indictor to test the pulse and hupothesis of COVID on the Australian property market. The timeframe which has been considered is between Jan 2020 and March 2022, a period of approximately 26 months. Conclusively we have seen NSW property market rising sharply during the early COVID months (refer to Question 5) and has been a gradually linear since then with a higher slope of growth.

To further enhance the evidence and test our hypothesis, we downloaded and mapped the NSW COVID confirmed cases from the state site. The results shows that although there is evidence of COVID having some impact on the initial sell of properties state wide. NSW COVID peak has been identified to be late December 2021 and January 2022, which has shown to have a dip in the Unit Sell and overall Cost for NSW. Traditionally spring and summer months have always shown strong volatility in the property market. This year though has shown a different trend and thus not entirely rejecting the hypothesis.

6. Future analysis on the topic¶

We have considered NSW as an indicator of Australian market trending of property market and COVID as a single variable which impacts the property market.

Trends for property and housing markets have a meaure of other variables including;

  1. lending rates from banks
  2. suburn of the property
  3. urban or rural
  4. house versus unit market
  5. COVID
  6. et-al

Analysis of these variables shall be considered to have a deeper understanding of first-time-home-buyer and their buying behaviour. As an example a slashed lending rate by the banks would have resulted in a higher populace to enter the property markets for the first time in 2019 and 2020. Similarly COVID situation and loss of jobs could have inversely impacted the property market. Banks and other lending institues have provided higher percentage of borrowing capability to potential home buyers.

There are clearly multiple variables impacting the housing market in Australia, the list given above are only some further analysis which could be done. Hypothesis and buying behaviour should have an integrated view of all such variables.
